The hurricane season in Cuba normally runs from June to November. Hurricane Michael will pass the west of Cuba on 8 October. The Cuban Government has three levels of warning before a hurricane: information, alert and alarm as the hurricane approaches. As of 1400h on 8 October, Isla de la Juventud and Pinar del Rio Province are in Alert. Havana, Artemisa, Matanzas and Myabeque are in information stage. You should monitor local and international weather updates from the US National Hurricane Center and follow the advice of the local authorities, including any evacuation orders, to move to alternative accommodation. Tour operators, hotels and owners of casas particulares should be aware of the advice in place in each area. See Natural disasters
You must take out comprehensive travel and medical insurance before you travel. You will be expected to present your insurance policy on arrival in the country.
Crime levels are low and mainly in the form of opportunistic theft. See Crime
Be cautious when travelling in Cuba. Driving standards are variable. See Road travel
UK health authorities have classified Cuba as having a risk of Zika virus transmission. For more information and advice, visit the website of the National Travel Health Network and Centre website.
Although there’s no recent history of terrorism in Cuba, attacks can’t be ruled out. See Terrorism
Most visits to Cuba are trouble free.
If you’re abroad and you need emergency help from the UK government, contact the nearest British embassy, consulate or high commission.
